Oh man. This. This. This. 

In @julie_rodgers’ book - “Outlove” - and the @netflix documentary just out this week - “Pray Away” - Julie walks us through conversion therapy, ex-gay ministries, pain and exclusion….all the way to freedom. She is a trustworthy, resilient leader and I LOVE HER. I also love her wife @amandahite and wish we were neighbors. 

This is powerful and important and vulnerable. So proud to be Julie’s friend. Links to her book and the Netflix doc in my stories.

node.title: POWERFUL conversation with one of my favorite people in the universe.

Saturday book talk! I want to tell you what we're reading in the Jen Hatmaker Book Club, because it's that good.
.
Clap When You Land — When I read this novel, I knew immediately that I wanted to put it in the Book Club. It’s YA — which by the way, YA is highly underrated. Some of the best writing and storytelling is in the YA genre. It is also written in verse. It is riveting and it is a masterpiece. 
.
The girls in our incredible private FB book club group are already singing its praises. You should be reading this with us. Come on over: JenHatmakerBookClub.com
.
Daring Greatly – This is what we’re going to be reading in September. It’s by your girl and mine: Brené Brown. And it’s easily one of the most impactful books I’ve read. Her special brand of wisdom and leadership is essential right now. Even if you’ve read it, it's worth another read.
.
You have until Aug. 5 to sign up for September book club. And, you’ll get our August gift as a bonus in addition to your September book box. It’s an adorable tumbler, so we can be tumbler twins.
.
But, in addition to all the goodies and book resources and FB Lives and podcasts, you’ll get immediate access to our community. Our community is Best in Show. We’re even raising money over there right now to send some special moms to a very special kind of Me Camp. It’s just a good place to be.
.
Join us! JenHatmakerBookClub.com

Here's the deal. As you know, I'm back from Me Camp. And the house has been run by young adult boys for three weeks, so you don't even want to know what the situation is. The fridge had the SAME food in it from three weeks ago, so I've been cleaning some really terrible vegetable soup out of the crisper drawer.
.
But, they kept my plants alive and that is all I asked.  .
Plants aside, our food situation is bleak. I am just trying to restore the house to some semblance of order. But, I somehow had the foresight to order HomeChef at Me Camp because she knew — SHE KNEW — I would want to have some food for the family and for me that doesn’t start with chips and end with salsa.
.
So, dinner is handled. It is solved. It is delivered. It is Sesame Chicken with Soy Sriracha Aioli. And it took me approximately, oh, four seconds to put together.
.
Okay, maybe three minutes. Because, we mixed up a sauce. But, really, this is as easy as possible. EVERY SINGLE THING IS INCLUDED. Even the pan. You don’t even need to wash a pan after dinner. .
We all need some life hacks and a little help from our friends — especially after a trip. And, Home Chef is my friend. And sometimes there is no time, or energy, or brain space, or groceries in a refrigerator run by boys for three weeks to figure out dinner. So, this is what I’m doing for me.
.
And, here’s the thing: Home Chef’s $90 off special is coming in hot again. 
.
YES, 90 DOLLARS OFF. Dinner is solved. You’re welcome! I’m putting the link for you in my Stories.
.
What are your life hacks when you get back from a trip?

What we can do together is often so much more powerful than what we can do alone. This is the magic. 
.
Remember the Texas Disaster Relief Fund through @legacycollective earlier this year? Well, we just made the final four grants to organizations serving those still desperately in need. And, it is such a beautiful thing. 
.
That makes a total of nine grants and $577K for the relief fund. Like what?! Your giving has made life-changing impact for so many.
.
Here is a FULL recap, so you can see how much of a difference this makes — you made: https://legacycollective.org/relief/. I’ll link it in my Stories, too.
.
We can do SO MUCH TOGETHER. When we combine our resources, our energy... it is just astonishing.
.
And, I saved the best for last, because in other news at @legacycollective, we've so far given 23 grants this year, amounting to more than $800K. And it is just July. That is all you. Every single member of Legacy. How incredible.
.
Want to be a part of this incredible group of likeminded people and make a difference? Come join us: https://legacycollective.org/join/

Beloveds, I just had a meeting with my therapist, Carissa, at Me Camp. Yes, even while I’m in Maine, I’m still prioritizing this part of my life. It’s another form of self-care — that I think we all need.
.
I talk about my therapist Carissa a lot. But, what you may not realize is that I meet with her online — not just in Maine, but even when I’m home in Austin. Because we are nowhere close in ZIP codes. But I have to say this: Online counseling works so well for me because I can do it from literally ANYWHERE. I just open my laptop, or hop on the phone, and boom!
.
That’s one of the many reasons I am such a proponent of Better Help. Because it is all virtual and accessible.
.
Look, I am at my OWN BEST when I stay committed to my regular therapy sessions. Because even the good, bright, or delightfully carefree ME CAMP IN MAINE times need attention, not just the darker, hibernation times.
.
Whatever season are you in, friends, I cannot encourage you more in caring for yourself with therapy. If you want to check out BetterHelp, this is a great way to get started.
.
Head over to Betterhelp.com/JenHatmaker to get access to a special pricing discount they’ve created especially for all of you.

I’m going to go ahead and put on record that the June gift in the Jen Hatmaker Book Club is one of my top three favorites.

I’m so excited to kick off summer book club reading with the most beautiful community on the internet — and our clever, funny, poignant June book: All Adults Here by Emma Straub.
.
We just have the most fun, not only with my favorite books and meaningful surprises — but also with summaries, discussion questions, live talks, author interviews, music playlists and so much more.
.
Join us for July! You have until June 5 to sign up. Jenhatmakerbookclub.com

We’re reading the most delicious culinary memoir in July called Blood, Bones & Butter — and, just trust me, it’s going to be a good month. 
.
Plus, we’re giving new members our bonus June gift — because I love it so much.
.
Give yourself the gift of books, women, community, friends this summer.
.
What’s not to love?! We’re waiting for you. Jenhatmakerbookclub.com

node.text:
Hold the Hatmakers close to your heart tonight. We had to say goodbye to the very best dog in the history of the world tonight. You know her. Our faithful, beloved companion Ladybird.

We were all there until the very end. We held her and kissed her and spoke into her ears. We told her all our favorite memories. We thanked her for loving us for 14 years, and for letting us love her. We soaked her fur with our tears. The very, very dearest family member. 

We are devastated beyond words. Our best friend. Our beloved. Thank you, Ladybird. You were a good, good girl. Such a good girl. We loved you. You brought us unending joy. We will miss you so much.

This is the face of a mom who has registered five kids for school since 2002, and here in The Year of Our Lord 2021, I *still* forgot to make appointments and do the things until one week before school starts. 

Dentist's office: "Our first opening is October 11th."
Doctor's office: "When did you want it? Tomorrow?? (sigh)" 
Ortho's office: "You want it not during school hours? The school that starts Thursday? We can see her in late September."
DMV: "First available appointment is November 4th." 
Target: "We have no more folders with brads."
Walmart: "Us either."
Office Max: "Same here." 

I need a House Manager. Here is your job description: 

You'll need to be live-in because it is a circus up in here. You will be on call 24 hours a day, because none of this ever ends. A recent sampling of the docket has included three new passports, one stolen passport, legal paperwork for name and birthdate changes, DMV appointments, drivers' ed, camp management, multiple doctors appointments, three family photo shoots, travel coordination for six people, therapy and medication oversight, geriatric dog intervention, yard and plant supervision, black hair governance, endless property upkeep, empty cup collecting, adult children relocation services, school registration, back-to-school anarchy, and teen sleep training because these fools have been up all night and asleep all day and next Thursday morning is going to be a serious Come to Jesus. 

Please apply below. I will provide the cooking and if you will also clean the kitchen, maybe we should just get married.

How can we make sure that our faith is in alignment with what is, arguably, one of the Bible's biggest call-outs, which is to love your neighbor as yourself?⁠
.⁠
Guest, @MalyndaHale, is making huge waves with the way that she intertwines her faith with justice and social activism and inclusion into her life's work. She has used her voice and social platform to create change within the realms of social justice and female empowerment and LGBTQ rights and veganism, and the Black Lives Matter movement. She's the host of her own podcast, called We Need To Talk, and it focuses on really crucial political and cultural and religious trends. You can see why I invited her today.⁠
.⁠
She says this at one point in our discussion, "Everything begins with a conversation" and after this hour you will maybe start to see where we are missing the mark as a society, in getting to the heart of our biggest differences with one another.⁠
.⁠
We talk about:⁠
.⁠
+The importance of empathy, how it can be DEEPLY rooted in our own privilege, and why flipping our script to uncover what it is the other person truly wants/needs in order to feel seen and understood can lead to so much progress⁠
.⁠
+The conversations and issues that Malynda sees creating the most friction for us as a society, that have the most misunderstanding or misinformation baked inside⁠
.⁠
+Breaking down the (somewhat problematic?) slogans of movements like "Black Lives Matter" and "Defund the Police" to get to the heart of what they are actually about and what they are trying to accomplish... which a lot of people do not know⁠
.⁠
+What "loving your neighbor" actually looks like and Malynda's beautiful "mic drop" response to "all lives matter" (that starts at the 42:56 mark)⁠
.⁠
I am so thrilled that she is here to talk through her own personal faith journey, why it is important to have difficult conversations around these ideas with the people closest to us, and how growing in our faith ultimately creates a more welcoming and safe and accepting and beautiful world for everyone. And if that isn't what we are put here to do, then I don't know what is.⁠
.⁠

Me and Remy just now: 

Remy: *telling me the longest explanation in the history of God's world about the plot of her book*

Me: *trying so hard because the parenting books said*

Remy: "...and then she was reincarnated as the book she was reading before, and she had to convince her friends she was in there, and at first they didn't believe her, because they couldn't hear her actual voice, but then after this one time when..."

Me: "Honey, you need to land the plane. I can listen to this for 10 more seconds at which point we need to be on the last page."

Remy: "Mom, you are supposed to be interested in the books I'm reading!"

Me: "I understand that, but the problem is that I'm not. I am not interested and don't want to know their names or any of it." 

Remy: "Oh my gosh, mom. Rude!"

Me: "Look, I've been listening to yall's long-ass descriptions of your books and night dreams and video games and weird shows since the year 2000. I just simply don't want to know about any of it anymore. My ears are exhausted. I'm sorry you're last, but your stories are just as boring as the other kids. You need to tighten it up."

Remy: "This is not good parenting."

But why are the stories so long. Why are the dreams so long. Why do all the details have to be said in words. We acted way too interested in their ramblings when they were little and now we're stuck. We created this. 

Our moms never listened to us. We raised ourselves in these streets with our friends and when we finally came home at dark to tell our moms about our adventures, they just told us to shut up because Magnum P.I. was on. We made our kids soft and now we have to listen to their anime stories.

It’s our birthday!!! Literally the best birthday twin in the whole known universe. 

We always start with birthday breakfast which Ben picks, and he strayed from his normal choice (Cracker Barrel) in favor of CFA, and the birthday boy gets whatever he wants. 

We talked about how far we’ve come since last August 7th. That last pic is us one year ago. I see it on our faces. We were three weeks out from our life imploding. Those smiles are strained and posed. They didn’t reach our eyes. We were hanging on for dear life. 

But this year, we have come SO FAR. Ben piled on me in my bed this morning and we just laughed. We now start the second round of “firsts.” We made it through them all. All the birthdays, holidays, anniversaries, seasons. The firsts are over. We did it. We did it together. 

And look how cute we are!! We are 47 and 18, and this kid is literally one of my life’s greatest joys. He is truly, truly the best. I got him fancy tools and he can’t quit staring at them. Senior year! MAKE IT STOP, JESUS. 

We are off to Fredericksburg with my whole family where we rented a bunch of tiny homes and plan to tear the town up. Look out for Jen and Ben today, everyone! It’s our day and ain’t nobody can tell us nothin’!

When you and your besties have been apart for a solid month, longest in the history of the friendship. 

We sat down and all started talking at once. We can talk over each other and interrupt and pile on and circle back and none of us ever miss a single word. It is an extraordinary skill set honed by one million hours of what I call "group talking." We have special ears for this but everyone else within hearing distance is immediately overwhelmed. The husbands usually just go out to the porch (they are all my husbands). 

Other things we can do: 

1. Lose the thread of a story because of over-talking and rabbit trails and pick it back up seamlessly 22 minutes later. 

2. Read each others' body language and know the exact second that person wants the rest of us to go home because it is late and apparently we all have jobs. 

3. Discern immediately when one of us wants to be talked into something or out of something then proceed accordingly. 

4. Two of us live on the same street, and the other two live on the same street, and all four houses are within 0.02 miles of each other, and we have one golf cart and four matching scooters to get to each others' houses because apparently this is too far to walk. 

5. We track each other on Find My Friends, and when I was on my date in Maine out by the ocean too long, Megan thought he drowned me and drug my body out to sea because she was stalking from Texas. 

What special skills do you and your friends have?

Today marks a first in the 4-year run of this punchy lil' #forthelovepodcast.⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
We're kickstarting a brand new series today called For the Love of Flipping the Script because not one of us came out of the last year-and-a-half unscathed. We all lost something which put many of us in the tough position of starting over, charting a new course, digging out & rebuilding. And that's what we're talking about in this series.⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
Today, I'm doing something I've never done on this show: talk about my own experience, about my life & the ways I have changed over the past few years - the long view, the short view & then the most recent changes in my life. What I've learned, what I got right, what I got wrong, what I'm taking with me into this next phase. I have walked through my personal sorrow with you, so you've watched it in real time. I know I can count on my community for the permission to be authentic.⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
Now, if you're hoping for some tasty morsels about the details of my divorce, you've come to the wrong place. That's no one's business but ours. But you will hear how I came through the darkest period of my life & found myself again. That's the bait on this hook.⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
If you are having to rework parts of your life unexpectedly, I am your witness that sometimes scorched earth turns into new life.⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
Can you lean into what is real/true & admit to your own self what is genuine?⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
Can you face this season in the spirit of growth & possibility?⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
Can you look forward instead of just backward?⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
What can you take responsibility for? What can you be thankful for?⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
What can you imagine or dream up?⁠⁠
.⁠⁠
Who can you be at the end of this? I believe that it is something spectacular, that it is someone resilient, stronger than you were before, wiser than you were before, kinder than you were before, braver than you were before.⁠⁠
.⁠⁠

node.text:
Quick trip to Nash to visit my friends at @able! Phenomenal! 

1. Peep my new uniform. That dress and those sneakers. This is who I am now. Not one, not two, but three women stopped me in the airport to ask where I got it, and since I get asked about my fashion never, this felt like a style anointing (head to toe by Able). It has pockets. Jesus loves us. 20JEN is your code to save 20%! I’ll link the look in my Stories. 

2. Sorry my hair looks like that. First off, it was raining when I left Austin at the crack of God’s dawn. Second, I’d tried on a bunch of faaaaaaall sweeeeeeaters at the Able HQ so I was sweaty and disastrous. Also I have developed an allergy to deodorant and cannot find one that doesn’t make my skin break out in a rash. And don’t @ me with natural deodorant. I like to call those Why Bother™️ because they work zero percent. As a person accustomed to the industrial strength turbo deodorant, this is the most distressing development of my adult life. But the sweaters! Get excited! Come on, fall! 

3. The cutie on the far right was styling a long cardigan on me, and she said: “Or you can take off everything underneath and button it up and wear it like a dress.” FIRST OF ALL, I died. Second of all, no I cannot. Third of all, I launched into a whole bit about my naughty sweater dress which we recorded so get excited for that later. Fourth of all, please try to think about your lady body wearing a buttoned up cardigan as a dress. You are welcome for your morning laugh. 

4. Dinner at @theoptimistnashville with these beautiful friends. The women around that table have lived some LIFE, and every one of them is stronger, wiser, kinder, braver, and more lovely for it. What an embarrassment of riches. What dear people to me. We laughed and cried over our oysters and shrimp, tears shed mainly because Marisa is allergic to butter and that feels real sad. 

5. Another gorgeous stay at @thompsonnashville where I wish I could live like Zac and Cody. Good morning, Nashville!

But what am I going to do about the deodorant? I need it. I am sweaty. I’ve tried every brand. Who will help me.
